Let \[f(x) =
\begin{cases}
x^2+9 &\text{if }x<-5, \\
3x-8&\text{if }x\ge-5.
\end{cases}
\]If $f(x)=10$, find the sum of all possible values of $x$.

extra.solution:
Cross multiplying, we obtain $ x+1 = 2(3x-1)$. (This is the same thing as multiplying both sides by both $3x-1$ and by $x+1$.)  Then, we solve for $x$: \begin{align*}
x+1 &= 2(3x-1)\\
\Rightarrow \qquad x+1 &= 6x-2\\
\Rightarrow \qquad-5x &= -3\\
\Rightarrow \qquad x &= \boxed{\frac{3}{5}}.
\end{align*}

Writing everything in terms of prime factorizations, the given expression is  \begin{align*}
&\sqrt{3 \cdot 5 \cdot 2^2 \cdot 3 \cdot 2^2 \cdot 7 \cdot 3^2 \cdot x^3} \\
& \qquad = \sqrt{(3^4 \cdot 2^4 \cdot x^2) \cdot (5 \cdot 7 \cdot x)} \\
& \qquad = \boxed{36x \sqrt{35x}}.
\end{align*}

