Using the quadratic formula, we find that the roots of the quadratic are $\frac{-5\pm\sqrt{5^2-4(3)(k)}}{6}=\frac{-5\pm\sqrt{25-12k}}{6}$. Since the problem tells us that these roots must equal $\frac{-5\pm i\sqrt{11}}{6}$, we have \begin{align*} \sqrt{25-12k}&=i\sqrt{11}
\\\Rightarrow\qquad \sqrt{25-12k}&=\sqrt{-11}
\\\Rightarrow\qquad 25-12k&=-11
\\\Rightarrow\qquad 12k&=36
\\\Rightarrow\qquad k&=\boxed{3}.
\end{align*}

question:
Expand and simplify completely: \begin{align*}
x\left(x(1+x)+2x\right)-3(x^2-x+2)
\end{align*}

extra.solution:
Begin by distributing in the innermost parentheses: \begin{align*}
&\ \ \ \ x\left(x(1+x)+2x\right)-3(x^2-x+2) \\&= x(x+x^2+2x) - 3(x^2-x+2)
\end{align*} Now, distribute again: \begin{align*}
x^2+x^3+2x^2-3x^2+3x-6
\end{align*} Finally, combine like terms to get \begin{align*}
\boxed{x^3+3x-6}
\end{align*}

